04405nam a22008055i 9780814723111DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147231117 a10.18574/97808147231112doi  a(DE-B1597)547072  a(OCoLC)819603546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE184.E2bB497 2007 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a305.8009732221 aBhatia, Sunil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Karma :bRace, Culture, and Identity in the Indian Diaspora /cSunil Bhatia. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQualitative Studies in Psychology ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 American Karma -- t2 Qualitative Inquiry and Psychology -- t3 Des-Pardes in the American Suburbia -- t4 Saris, Chutney Sandwiches, and "Thick Accents" -- t5 Racism and Glass Ceilings -- t6 Analyzing Assignations and Assertions -- t7 Imagining Homes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Indian American community is one of the fastest growing immigrant communities in the U.S. Unlike previous generations, they are marked by a high degree of training as medical doctors, engineers, scientists, and university professors.American Karma draws on participant observation and in-depth interviews to explore how these highly skilled professionals have been inserted into the racial dynamics of American society and transformed into "people of color." Focusing on first-generation, middle-class Indians in American suburbia, it also sheds light on how these transnational immigrants themselves come to understand and negotiate their identities.Bhatia forcefully contends that to fully understand migrant identity and cultural formation it is essential that psychologists and others think of selfhood as firmly intertwined with sociocultural factors such as colonialism, gender, language, immigration, and race-based immigration laws.American Karma offers a new framework for thinking about the construction of selfhood and identity in the context of immigration. This innovative approach advances the field of psychology by incorporating critical issues related to the concept of culture, including race, power, and conflict, and will also provide key insights to those in anthropology, sociology, human development, and migrant studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEast Indian AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aEast Indian AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 4aAmerican. 4aKarma. 4aabout. 4aconstruction. 4acontext. 4aframework. 4aidentity. 4aimmigration. 4aoffers. 4aselfhood. 4athinking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814723111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814723111.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK